  "final_text": "I'll read the UART peripheral state and the RCC clock tree in parallel so I can compute the actual baud rate and spot the mismatch.\nUSART2 is completely unconfigured \u2014 `UE=0`, `BRR=0`, `TE=0`. I need to see the full RCC output (clock source for USART2, APB1 enable bit) and also check USART1 and LPUART1 in case the firmware is using a different peripheral.\nAll three UARTs are at reset state (BRR=0, UE=0) \u2014 the debugger is catching the chip before firmware even initializes UART. I need to reset the target, let it run past init, then halt and re-read USART2.\nUSART2 is still at reset state after 500ms of running \u2014 confirming the flashed firmware doesn't initialize UART at all. Let me check what the MCU is actually doing and inspect the fault/crash state, then look at what's on the VCP line.\nThis tells the whole story. Let me check the IWDG in case a watchdog is driving rapid resets, and look at the VCP subcommand syntax:\nI now have the complete picture. Here's the full diagnosis:\n\n---\n\n## Root cause: firmware never exits `Reset_Handler` \u2014 no UART is active at all\n\n### What the registers show\n\n| Peripheral | Key fields | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **USART2** (VCP UART) | `UE=0`, `TE=0`, `RE=0`, `BRR=0` | **Never initialized** |\n| **USART1** | Same \u2014 all reset values | Never touched |\n| **LPUART1** | Same \u2014 all reset values | Never touched |\n| **RCC** | MSI=4 MHz, PLL off, HSE off, HSI off | Pure reset-state clocks |\n| **IWDG** | `PR=0`, `RLR=4095`, `SR=0` | Not started \u2014 no watchdog reset loop |\n| **SCB faults** | `CFSR=0`, `HFSR=0` | No hard/bus/mem fault |\n| **VCP capture** | Silent at 115200 | Zero bytes transmitted |\n\n### The firmware is stuck in startup\n\n```\ncallstack: Reset_Handler @ startup_stm32l476rgtx.s:62  (PC=0x08001474)\nLR = 0xFFFFFFFF  \u2190 never returned from startup; never reached main()\nall GPRs = 0\n```\n\nThe chip re-executes `Reset_Handler` every time \u2014 it's looping in the BSS zero-fill or hanging in the `bl SystemInit` call. `SystemInit` on this board commonly gets stuck waiting for `HSERDY` (HSE-ready flag) if the CubeMX clock config targets HSE/PLL but the external crystal path is broken or not present in the loaded binary.\n\nThe \"garbage\" on the terminal is **not a baud-rate mismatch** \u2014 the MCU is not transmitting anything. What the terminal is seeing is either line noise during ST-LINK USB enumeration/reset cycles, or it's open on the wrong port entirely.\n\n### What to fix\n\n**The terminal side** \u2014 set your terminal to **115200 8N1** (the NUCLEO-L476RG VCP standard); that's already correct for any CubeL4 UART example.\n\n**The firmware side** is where the real problem is. Two likely causes:\n\n1. **`SystemInit` spin-waiting on HSE** \u2014 the loaded binary calls `HAL_RCC_OscConfig` targeting HSE and loops forever at the `while (!__HAL_RCC_GET_FLAG(RCC_FLAG_HSERDY))` check. Verify the `.ioc` / `system_stm32l4xx.c` clock config. If you want MSI-only (easiest on NUCLEO), set `RCC_OscInitStruct.OscillatorType = RCC_OSCILLATORTYPE_MSI` with no HSE.\n\n2. **Wrong firmware flashed** \u2014 the fixture path points to a plain `GPIO-IOToggle` example that has **no UART init at all**. You need to flash a binary that actually calls `MX_USART2_UART_Init()` with the correct BRR for your clock tree.\n\n**Correct USART2 BRR for 115200 baud at 4 MHz MSI (reset clock, no PLL):**\n```\nBRR = 4,000,000 / 115,200 = 34.72 \u2192 0x23 (rounds to \u2248 115,107 baud, < 0.1% error)\n```\nOnce you have a firmware that reaches `main()` and calls `MX_USART2_UART_Init()`, set your terminal to **115200 8N1** and it will be readable.\n\n**Next step I'd suggest**: `stm32 debug snapshot` with a new firmware that includes a UART println in `main()` \u2014 or share the `system_stm32l4xx.c` clock config so we can identify exactly where `Reset_Handler` is spinning."
}